Duel on knife edge: MP3 player against mobile phones.
We advise you on your choice
While almost any mobile phone can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can yet make a phone call.
Therefore, of course, it looks like it is better to buy only one phone.
Despite all this, there are plenty of reasons why you should acquire an independent player.
The choice depends entirely on the type of use and the claims of the future owner.
Surely it is hard to buy a great expensive record player at home to listen to the latest album by Maxim Turbulenc.
Once such musical novelties do not appear on LPs, and from a qualitative point of view, there is no objective reason for this either.
However, if you have LPs with art rock, jazz or blues on the shelf, you’re probably dreaming of at least one of them.
This is also simplified with the music on travel, i.e. with compressed music - music in MP3 format.
Here, too, there are price and quality categories.
For some, it may not be acceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a player, but a pink-floyd fan will probably not be able to handle headphones for twenty crowns from the market.
Two extremes, between which there is enough space for everyone.
The selection is wide.
The life of the batteries is also crucial.
Some good music players can play much more than just music, but what mobile phones can do, they don’t even insinuately.
No modern device is as universal as the phone.
In addition to the primary functions, the phone and the sims, it can play music and videos, record both, it has a better, sometimes a worse camera and maybe it can also navigate.
And if you include the smart phones and communicators, you almost have a small computer in your pocket.
It’s a little wonder, because no refrigerator can grill and no television can photograph.
However, the universality of mobile phones also brings with it disadvantages.
However, the more features you use on your phone, the more often you will need to recharge it.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy eaters.
Few mobile phones can play music longer than ten to twelve hours, most of the time it is much less.
In this regard, music players (especially the simplest ones) are significantly more powerful.
That’s why you should expect cheap phones to be able to play music for no more than a few hours.
If you then still make phone calls from time to time, for safety, you prefer to buy a charger for the office - this also applies to more expensive devices.
With MP3 players, you won’t have this problem, even the less good ones keep at least 9 hours of continuous operation with one time charging out.
Another problem is when you want to transfer the music to your mobile phone.
Unfortunately, only a small part of the devices have a USB connector, and it is also not possible to connect any mobile phone directly to a PC without special software.
Of course, you can transfer the music directly to a storage medium, but only a few card readers can cope with the tiny memory cards used in mobile phones without reduction.
For players, you do not need any special software except for exceptions (iPod).
You only need to feed the device via USB port with music from your PC.
Most mobile phones and players create a music library themselves, ordered by the name of the performer, the title of the album, the genre or, for example, the rating by users.
Some devices only represent the tree structure of the address directory, similar to the Windows Explorer, some can do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Players are easier to use, mobile phones can
When choosing a specific device, you should inquire in particular about the battery life, the storage capacity, the quality and type of sound and, of course, the ease of use.
If for you music is primarily a backdrop and you only listen to it briefly every day, for example in the tram, then any mobile phone that plays MP3 files is enough.
What almost any mobile phone can do.
You also don’t have to control which music formats a mobile phone or player can handle.
MP3 create all, and most of the music you get will be in this format right now.
The format is one of the most common, and in addition, most devices can also play music in WMA format.
Less common is AAC (a format that Apple and its iPods use).
Better phones also allow you to buy music online.
You only need to access the corresponding pages of one provider (or another provider) via the mobile internet, and you can already buy a song or album.
This service can in and of itself be a striking argument for why you should buy a music phone.
Unfortunately, the offer of the providers is poor and is mostly limited to fast radio hits.
The prices are not the lowest either.
In general, however, it is assumed that precisely this type of music sales (whether via GSM, the Internet or wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people carry their phones with them.
If you feel like listening to yourself, grab your phone in your jacket pocket while the player is at home.
However, it depends on whether you always carry headphones or at least one wireless hands-free device.
If not, you can resort to the built-in speaker that almost every phone has, but only the fewest MP3 players.
Probably the biggest advantage of music phones will be in the price for many.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three thousand crowns.
For three and four thousand crowns you will get a very decent walkman.
The biggest handicap for most will be that there are no normal headphones.
The best and most technically sophisticated phones with a 3.5mm opening for normal headphones cost up to fifteen thousand crowns.
The advantage of the players in turn lies in the easy operation.
The simplest – and not necessarily the cheapest (see selection) – player can really serve anyone.
A minimum of functions, the similarity in operation to the formerly normal cassette recorder or, for example, the turntable is obvious.
There is no danger of a collision in the form of an erroneously employed mobile Internet and a subsequent horrendous invoice for data transmissions.
Which device should you use?
Even the cheapest phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for interchangeable storage media (type M2, microSD, etc.).
Even if you buy a corresponding card, two thousand crowns will suffice.
Attention, though.
For the basic models, only cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB are usually supported.
Only the most expensive ones can also read 8GB memory cards.
If you already own a mobile phone and want to buy an inexpensive MP3 player, go to Cowon, Creativ, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you do not have to put more than 1100 crowns on the table.
Be among the more sophisticated listeners, prefer to take specialized phones - Walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some from Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have stand-alone buttons for MP3, and the ease of use is close to that of a single MP3 player.
The widest is Sony Ericsson, whose mobile phones from the Walkman series have the same user interface as the individually sold MP3 players.
The same services in the same price category of up to four thousand crowns, but with a higher storage capacity (up to 16 GB) and a long battery life (usually 15 hours, maximum up to 35 hours) provide you with MP3 players from the above-mentioned manufacturers.
The first virtual provider is already coming to the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, the Czech providers offer practically all services, as they are also offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classics at lower prices.
Maybe he won't wait long.
That the Czech mobile service providers are among the most expensive in Europe, we have already reported on Mobil.cz many times.
By the way, this was also confirmed by the Telecommunications Authority <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, which pointed out that the price of an SMS is higher here than in the rest of the European Union.
After the European Commission’s latest steps in the regulation of roaming charges, it is likely that there will be a paradoxical situation – for some customers of Czech mobile providers, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
Why is it that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, it lacks the competition that really makes a battle announcement.
Perhaps it sounds paradoxical, because in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of far more than 100%.
On the other hand, mobile operators like to scold that there is an extremely high level of competition in the Czech market.
Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99>ák, chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>) often agrees with this, who had often said in the past that there was no room for another provider in the Czech Republic.
It is likely that a classic provider with its own network will no longer have a lot of opportunities (by the way, it would probably hardly find frequencies).
But there is another option - a virtual provider.
Especially the entry of virtual providers into the mobile market brought with it a significant price reduction, to which also the classic mobile providers had to respond.
Even before the entry of such companies as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile, there were similar voices on the market in the UK as in the Czech Republic.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can be really successful.
By the way, it doesn’t take long to look for examples.
In February, we reported on the launch of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider managed to attract more than 100 thousand customers and thus rise to the fifth largest provider in the country.
Behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic, among others.
The advantage of virtual providers is that you can focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to function effectively, virtual providers need far fewer customers than a traditional provider.
You don’t need to have a relatively high cost of building, operating and maintaining a mobile network.
In the world, the virtual providers usually profile themselves as low-cost companies - they offer cheap phone calls and SMS, which is often accompanied by a less extensive range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half as cheap as its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a pretty good move to bet on a non-cliché target group.
This provider is specifically aimed at men.
“Real guys choose Mobilking – the provider they like and can trust,” said David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept as in Poland could also take hold in the Czech Republic.
Vodafone spokesperson Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> also doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the service offering."
In the Czech Republic there is no chance, the mobile operators say
However, it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile carrier conquers the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about an expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not look very hopeful.
Mobilking will be more likely to enter the market in other countries of our region," said Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>ková, press secretary for the financial group Penta, in a telephone call for Mobil.cz.
Indirectly, it confirmed that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not particularly inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything possible to ensure that no potential competitor is created.
The GTS Novera Group has long shown its interest in launching a virtual mobile provider, which wants to take another step in order to become a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
"We have a great interest in offering our customers not only landline but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the earlier, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this option with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them, we have already been able to make progress in negotiations," said the group's press spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
Maybe better times are coming.
Unofficial information indicates that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
So far, however, this is surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
"At this moment, we do not assume that there is room in the Czech Republic for a full-fledged virtual provider.
The Czech market has large specifics compared to other markets.
So far, we have not been approached by anyone with a complex and serious project in this area," says Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88> from the press department of Telefónica O2 in his statement to Mobil.cz.
Other providers also point to the specifics of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová rarely agrees with O2’s statement: “So far, we have not found a viable and mutually beneficial project to build on.”
“On the T-Mobile network, hardly any virtual provider will appear by the end of the year.
At this moment, we would have to have a concrete offer to think in the short term.”
Vodafone is focusing its attention on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> says: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual providers, especially in the area of cost sharing and infrastructure.
This is what we see as the best from the customer’s point of view.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile internet.”
The responsible authorities - with the providers hand in hand
The approach of the mobile operators is easy to understand, another provider would be more competition, this would lead to falling prices and thus to a decrease in profits.
So why should we make it easier for such a competitor to enter the market?
The fact that the providers can pull on a string when it comes to something also proves the long back and forth about the creation of U:fon.
Probably the strongest pressure towards <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> was coming from T-Mobile when U:fon was launched.
This is also evidenced by the publicly available information on the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> websites.
Now, however, U:fon is suitable as an argument why you should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová commented: "The competitive environment of the mobile market has also recently been strengthened by the market entry of a fourth mobile provider.
Taking into account the character of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that a new player would place high demands on the market itself and above all on its services."
However, in view of this approach of the mobile operators, the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities is astonishing.
This is not just the attitude of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, which unfortunately, unlike the United Kingdom and other advanced countries, does not have the competence to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
It has exclusively the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
This, however, related to this whole problem his very typical attitude.
"The entry into the market of a virtual mobile provider would then be possible after a contract has been concluded between a mobile provider and a virtual provider for the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
So far, no such contract has been concluded, because the offer of potential prospects was probably not sufficiently interesting for the classic providers," said Kristián Chalupa of the Department of External Relations of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS in his reply to our request.
Representatives of the providers would not be surprised by such a formulation.
This is more than questionable by an authority that should represent consumer interests and, among other things, ensure that no one abuses its position on the market.
In particular, when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Abroad, where virtual providers work normally, it is to be observed that their market entry has contributed to a price reduction in mobile phone services."
However, pressure on the correct functioning of the market and a price cut are probably not in the interests of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
Really shocking in this case is the almost touching harmony of the three mobile phone providers, which results from their reactions.
The question of whether it is really just a coincidence is obvious.
Just as the absolutely equal price of gasoline at the petrol stations is certainly just coincidence and the result of a tough competition.
"The Authority has not detected any evidence in this case that indicates anti-competitive action and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way in the matter.
None of the providers has a dominant market position, so they do not have the corresponding increased responsibility for their actions in the market.
The necessary instruments to open up the mobile market for virtual providers are also likely to be lacking for the telecommunications regulator,” Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, prepared by <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, according to which telecommunications is a single market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech mobile operators has a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - for the market entry of a virtual provider, the consent of the network operator is always necessary.
And the mobile operator has - logically - a monopoly on its network.
This means that it necessarily assumes a dominant position in a particular segment.
But even if one does not go along with this argument, it should at least be a warning for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS that three mobile operators are acting strikingly similarly.
Complaints by a number of interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) prove that they encounter very similar obstacles in negotiations with all providers.
The shifting of responsibility to <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> is then a fairly common trick in telecommunications services, with which the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS distances itself from the whole matter.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, the recently adopted amendment to the Telecommunications Act failed to enforce the extension of the competences of <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> in the area of economic competition in telecommunications, although a number of experts had promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS need only know all too well, but they probably have other interests.
It's okay when no one's looking
First of all, the functioning of any pseudovirtual providers remains unnoticed, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks.
They are companies that issue their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but are only partially public.
Usually these are companies that operate in the field of multi-level marketing.
Own mobile phone services offer, for example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach the chosen ones.
The joke of the matter is that the company appears to the operator as a classic corporate customer who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, he then receives special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar resale.
"If there are cases you describe, then it may be a violation of the contractual conditions that we will then deal with, which may lead to a termination of cooperation with the corresponding company," Martina Kemrová replied to our question on this problem.
However, it is quite unlikely that such a thing will not be around with the managers of the mobile phone providers.
Especially in the case of the three mentioned companies, it can be thousands of customers.
However, no operator opposes such an approach.
They do not receive negligible profits from the activities of these companies, and at the same time, unlike the actual virtual providers, they are not affected by the actual official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> points out that "the law allows such types of speculation, despite everything, the services of these companies are only used by a very small percentage of customers.
In addition, they must accept that the SIM card in their phone does not run on their name, so they cannot have it fully like the normal customers of the mobile providers.
But that alone would have to happen to the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> at least strange.
There is also another question for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
If mobile providers close their eyes to such an action, why are they locking themselves against a virtual provider?
It should be added that the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has quite strong competences to detect such activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the declaration of the providers that they do not know of it and their terms and conditions would prohibit this.
When the Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As has already been stressed several times in the text, the market entry of virtual providers led to a significant decrease in prices for the various services.
In practically all countries where virtual providers have emerged, the classic providers have tried to prevent their emergence practically more or less.
The arguments they used were practically identical - a market that was too small or too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In the highly developed countries, however, regulators intervened at these moments, which did not try to protect the interests of mobile providers, but rather those of their customers.
Whether through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they achieved that the first virtual operator was created, and this was followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are throwing the whole case like a hot potato.
Based on our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that ambiguity in the competencies in these cases is more than favorable.
But let's not throw the gun into the grain.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider will soon appear, the Czech mobile market may soon get back on track.
If a provider allows the creation of a virtual mobile service provider, <0xC3><0x9A>OHS will not remain idle when it comes to rejecting (discriminating) other interested parties.
And the Czechs will finally not make phone calls more expensive than the rest of Europe.
