The Prague transport companies will also transport on a chip for the first time on Wednesday
Wednesday, 1 October 2008, will go down in the history of Prague’s transport companies as a date on which the first passengers to enter a subway, tram or bus who carry an electronic coupon in their pocket instead of a paper ticket.
These can currently be bought by about one hundred thousand people who have the chip card open card.
Passengers can purchase a 30-day, 90-day or yearly coupon (valid from 1 January 2009) and have it displayed on their chip card at the information centres and branches of the transport companies at the metro stations Muzeum, M<0xC5><0xAF>stek, Nádra<0xC5><0xBE><0xC3><0xAD> Hole<0xC5><0xA1>ovice, And<0xC4><0x9B><0xC5><0x9B>lovy Let<0xC5><0x9B>lis, Roz.
The coupons have also been available since yesterday via the Internet on the pages of the transport companies www.dpp.cz.
The service was used until the afternoon hours of more than four hundred customers.
Those who use the Internet sale can really forget the issue window in the subway stations, where until now they had to wait regularly in long lines for their paper tickets.
You buy the coupon over the Internet, it is played on the open card in one of the thirteen branches of the city library.
"At these points, travelers are also provided with a desk with trained staff, which advises interested parties on their online purchases and also displays the coupon on the map," said project spokesman Martin Opatrn<0xC3><0xBD>.
