The Sudeten demanded a referendum from the United States.
The Sudeten Germans had asked in 1945 for the annexation of the Bohemian Forest to the United States.
This is evident from a letter which is stored in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we would at least like to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
With such a wish, some groups of Sudeten Germans reportedly approached the US president in 1945.
This is reflected, among other things, in a letter preserved in a private archive, which is now kept in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
The Germans of Krumau in the letter ask the American president not to allow the return of the "Sudetengau" - which was taken on the basis of the Munich agreement by Hitler - to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation correctly and really want to be sure of the words that the American units do not enter German territory as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," it said in a letter signed with the words "People who are at heart with the fate of the Sudeten".
Since the Sudeten Germans’ accession to Czechoslovakia suggests that they would expect brutality, ruthlessness, incomprehension, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter ask the American president to assume protection over the Bohemian Forest for today and forever.
“We cannot believe that, without regard to the view of a quarter million inhabitants of this area, you confer on a foreign state that oppresses and eliminates minorities and has contributed nothing at all to the victory of the Allies,” the letter reads.
The reason why the authors are not able to sign is allegedly the fear of revenge cravings of the "Czech oppressors".
If the U.S. president has doubts about the attitude of the Bohemian Forest Germans, it would be sufficient if he would initiate a referendum in the Bohemian Forest on whether the inhabitants would become part of the U.S. or live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text of the letter may sound somewhat naive in today’s knowledge of post-war history, it does, in the opinion of some contemporary witnesses, paint a good picture of the expectations of the Sudeten Germans at that time.
Although the Bohemian Germans had to at least foresee that they would be negotiating their deportation from the Republic, only a few of them admitted such a possibility at all.
Some waited for the United States and Britain to negotiate some kind of autonomy for the Sudeten.
Others thought they could just stay in Czechoslovakia.
This is also confirmed by the famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, who comes from Budweis.
He was employed in the Baltic Sea navy as a Budweiser German during the war.
When he came into British captivity at the end of the war and was taken to a prisoner-of-war camp in Holstein, dozens of other Bohemian Germans came to him to teach them Czech.
“They believed that if they came home, the Czech would suit them,” Chalupa said.
None of the German prisoners of war who had lived in Czechoslovakia before the war, in his opinion, expected that he would be expelled from the republic on the basis of the Bene<0xC5><0xA1> decrees.
