Rats also have feelings.
Does a rat or a goat flee when in danger mean that they also feel fear?
Neuroscientist Joseph LeDoux is convinced that many animals also have feelings.
Only how can you check if they feel the same if they behave similarly to us?
For several years, the Internet magazine "Edge" has published articles by famous scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series selected answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else having been able to prove this so far where we cannot even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case, we can at least hope that all human brains have the same basic configuration.
However, as soon as we turn to other species and address questions of sensation or, more generally, of consciousness, we enter impassable terrain because the hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: it sets itself up dead, flees or attacks.
Humans behave similarly, as some scientists conclude from a comparable subjective experience.
But I don't believe that.
Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to that of animals.
On the one hand, the circuits almost always associated with human consciousness include the lateral prefrontal cortex (because of its involvement in short-term memory and execution/control functions).
This broad region is much more developed in man than in the rest of the primates and seems to be completely lacking in other creatures.
At least in those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including the knowledge of who we are, and the ability to plan and decide, there is reason to assume that man is even different from the other primates.
Another dramatic characteristic may lie in the linguistic nature of man: Since so much of his experience is connected with language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness did not depend on language, it would certainly influence it, so that animal consciousness, however it may be, is probably very different from most of our states of consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to determine what consciousness may look like in other animals.
If, as something internal and subjective, it cannot be measured or analyzed on the basis of our own experience because of the special hardware, then his research presents us with great problems.
Most of my remarks relate to the content of conscious experience, but there is also another aspect of consciousness that is likely to be more scientifically accessible.
