Debate on bilingual education: Education in an English-speaking environment
In this issue of Education Watch, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss the positions of candidates for bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, Senior Research Fellow in California Studies and Senior Director in the Department of Educational Sciences at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is a co-author of the book "Not as Good as You Think: Why the Middle Class Needs a School Choice".
Addressing Hispanic voters is a complicated task.
Barrack Obama’s proposals on education are a typical example of this.
Obama’s election campaign mentions that “the likelihood of successful completion of school among African-American and Hispanic students is lower than among white students” — which is true.
To close this gap, Obama’s education plan specifically recommends, among other things, a bilingual transitional phase in education for those who first learn English.
Nevertheless, the question for Obama is whether his commitment to bilingual education, which focuses on teaching in languages other than English, contradicts his interest in reducing the gap in school performance.
Take Sixth Street Prep, an elementary school in eastern Los Angeles.
The majority of students are Hispanic and come from low-income families.
More than a third of students, many of whom have only recently been in the country, learn English.
Nevertheless, in 2008, an astonishing 100 percent of fourth-grade students passed the state exam in math at a good level.
Also surprisingly, 93 percent of children in their fourth year of school were rated as good in the English exam.
This astonishing success was achieved by methods other than those favored by Obama.
Sixth Street School focuses on review and practice, constant control of knowledge, and an attitude that tolerates no exceptions.
In addition, the school practices the approach of education in an English-speaking environment, which is exactly what Obama should consider, according to school principal Linda Mikels.
This approach emphasizes the almost exclusive use of the English language in technical instruction.
Ms. Mikels, who rejects the idea of bilingual education, told me that the school would have a remarkable success with a student who had just arrived from Mexico.
“It works,” she noted, “it works for us.”
Would Obama take a school like the Sixth Street Prep as a model for other schools with a large share of Latin American and other English-learning students?
The school’s achievements would make the answer to this question easy, but the educational policy positions within its own party (the national picture associations have long supported the idea of bilingual education) and its own consistent support of bilingual education make predictions about Obama’s response uncertain.
While he agrees with the point that immigrants should learn English, he recently trivialized the issue by noting that people should stop worrying about legislation aimed at “English-only.”
Instead, he said, “You’re supposed to make sure your child can speak Spanish.”
If Obama really wants to close the gap, he should carefully consider educational models that work rather than despise and trivialize them.
Oil prices are falling as a result of renewed fears about the economy
Oil prices fell sharply on Monday due to fears that even the U.S. bailout plan for financial markets could not suffice to revive the economy.
Crude oil forward trading on the New York Stock Exchange fell 7 percent to $99.80 per barrel in the morning session.
Since last Monday, the price has dropped by more than $20.
In the past two weeks, goods markets have been shaken by both the financial turmoil on Wall Street and strong cyclones in the Gulf of Mexico.
After prices peaked at $145.29 per barrel in July, they dropped to nearly $90 per barrel this month, then climbed again as a result of enormous uncertainty in the financial markets.
On Monday, investors again showed concern, although congressional representatives had announced that they had agreed on a rescue plan over the weekend, which should be the largest in history.
This news was overshadowed by new concerns that the financial crisis is still far from over.
In the final chapter of the growing crisis, Citigroup is said to be buying up Wachovia Corporation’s banking business, according to a government statement on Monday.
In the meantime, Belgian, Dutch and Luxembourg governments have partly nationalized the European financial group Fortis.
According to analysts at Barclays Capital, despite the tense negotiations that took place over the weekend and led to a rescue plan, it seems that it has not managed to revive the mood in the markets.
As the economic situation continues to deteriorate, demand for goods, including oil, is expected to decline further.
Analysts at Deutsche Bank have written in a statement to investors that forecasts for global capital markets, interest rates and exchange rates have become extremely uncertain.
We believe, they continue to write, that the goods markets will also be affected.
“From the perspective of the goods markets, we are most concerned about whether the U.S. virus is spreading worldwide, especially to China.”
The bank’s analysts have downgraded its oil consumption expectations due to weak economic growth for the coming year and lowered its oil and gas price forecasts for 2009 by 20%.
