Rugged Gebrselassie beats his world record
Haile Gebrselassie from Ethiopia has shown once again why some consider him the best long-distance runner of all time after breaking his own record at the Berlin Marathon on Sunday and becoming the first person to make the 42.2 km track in less than 2 hours and 4 minutes.
With the victory on the flat course in 2:03:59, Gebrselassie improved his previous result of 2:04:26 by 27 seconds, which he had reached last year in Berlin.
Gebrselassie, 35, has thus set his 26th world record in his versatile career, in which he achieved at least one world championship title or a world record on every track from one kilometer to the marathon.
Last month, Gebrselassie skipped the Olympic Marathon in Beijing, fearing that air pollution could exacerbate his asthma problems.
Instead, he signed up for the competition in Berlin.
In almost ideal conditions – at sun and 9 degrees at the start and 13 degrees at the finish – Gebrselassie has won at an average speed of 4 minutes and 43 seconds per mile.
Since track runners like Gebrselassie and Paul Tergat from Kenya have switched on long distances, the record time for marathon in the last 10 years has fallen by more than 2 minutes since Ronaldo da Costa from Brazil won in 1998 in Berlin with the result of 2:06:05.
After his victory on Sunday, Gebrselassie told the press that he had cramps in his calf two weeks ago and was therefore unable to train for a week.
Obviously, he was refreshed after a break and did not come back rusty.
“I’m so happy,” he told reporters.
“Everything went perfectly.
I resumed training a week ago and had some concerns today, but in the end everything was great.”
He has been criticized – especially in Kenya, Ethiopia’s rival from East Africa – for overly orchestrating his races, avoiding many of the world’s best marathon stars in general, relying too much on the race leaders as if it were a track race, and setting world records above competition.
But this criticism hardly hurts the size of Gebrselassie as a long-distance runner.
Accompanied by four Kenyans on Sunday, Gebrselassie had reached the center of the track in 1:02:04.
Two Kenyan elite runners, James Kwambai and Charles Kamathi, have continued to challenge Gebrselassie after the pacemakers had subsided.
A little more than three miles before the finish, Gebrselassie made his final start to separate from Kwambai, who arrived second in 2:05:36, improving his best time by almost 5 minutes.
Kamathi finished third in 2:07:48.
For women, Irina Mikitenko, originally from Kazakhstan and now German, finished a remarkable year by showing the seventh fastest result of all time with 2:19:19.
The world record of 2:15:25 is held by Paul Radcliff from Great Britain.
Last spring, 36-year-old Mikitenko had surprisingly won the London Marathon in 2:24:14.
She missed the games in Beijing due to issues described as a back injury, but recovered to win in Berlin and improve her best time in her third marathon by five minutes.
She has skilfully planned her run by first having a quartet of Ethiopian and Kenyan runners torn out, but overtaken after 30 kilometers.
Askale Tafa Magarsa of Ethiopia finished second in 2:21:31, while Helena Kiprop of Kenya finished third in 2:25:01.
The pride and hardships in the life of the black population, in a city of a very special kind
Hidden between the exuberances of the theme parks around Orlando, a few miles from the glittering, noisy and gigantic hustle and bustle, lies a quiet city where the pride and complications of African-American culture come to light.
Eatonville, the first all-black city in the country and the hometown of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as easy to describe as Hurston did in 1935: "the city with 5 lakes, three croquettes, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, more than enough guavas, 2 schools and no prison."
Nowadays it is a pilgrimage site.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have come to the annual Zora! festival in Eatonville to commemorate the most famous author of the Harlem Renaissance.
And yet the city it describes – and which made it a tourist destination by including it in the Florida travel guide, which was produced by the Federal Writer Project at the time of the depression – is and remains in many ways a place of a very special kind.
Eatonville is as independent, devoted and private as it was in the 1930s when Hurston wrote that rural black communities in Florida often refused to share their true thoughts with the white man who “knows so little about us that he doesn’t know what he misses.”
Even today, in a year in which a black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, calls for an open conversation about race relations, many here are still tired of being watched by outsiders.
“We are very concerned about how our story is told,” said Hortense Jones, 59, from birth to a resident of the city and a parishioner of the city’s oldest church.
It must be right.”
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and struggle.
It is both a historical example of the black movement and a municipality of nearly 2,400 inhabitants, where the poverty rate is twice as high as the national average.
It is, on the one hand, a stronghold of literature and, on the other hand, an example of the sometimes condemned, sometimes praised, black culture of the rural South, which has its roots in American slavery.
It is not surprising that residents here are both proud and on their guard.
And so the concerns about Eatonville's image actually started with Zora, as everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced the world to her hometown in books that came from the heart and were written in verbal form, such as "Mules and Men" (1953) and "Their Eyes were watching God" (1973).
Five paragraphs in the Florida Guide changed the city, which is very close to Route 77, a road that leads through the often-forgotten center of Florida, to the scenes of black history and human drama.
Like Oskar in both real life and literature, Hurston led Reader to the shop of Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then turned to more private affairs.
"Away from the road to the left," she wrote, "is the brown-white-painted modern school, with its neat gardens and playgrounds, which Howard Miller always cares about, though he can hardly read and write."
She also mentioned widow Dash's new husband and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of all kinds and whatever-always-fits classrooms."
In just a few hundred words, Hurston associated Eatonville with self-government, but also illiteracy, second marriage, and sex.
This was certainly not a travel guide.
In fact, this was not a portrait that was appreciated by everyone.
“Zora described things as they were,” said 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of the Johnson girls who perpetuated Hurston by quoting the men who sang songs about her beauty that were full of sexual allusions.
She added: “Some people didn’t like it.”
Hurtson is still remembered here as a lively eccentric who returned regularly after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Augustus Franklin, 77, remembered that when Hurston came to the city, she did so mostly without warning, in a noisy Chevrolet, smoking and dressed in trousers, in a city that even today imagines something about her venerable style of clothing.
According to Mr. Franklin, most of the residents were fascinated, while many scorned them.
“People were always happy to see Zora,” Mr. Franklin said.
But "she never stayed too long," he added as he waved in his chair, on a rearward terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized.
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books sold out.
Along with most of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten her.
Although she was once a famous author, a contemporary Langstin Hughes, and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an anonymous tomb in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she lived.
In Eatonville, there was no large memorial service, no public readings on a large scale.
“I don’t think they understood their contribution to the world or their heritage in the least,” said Valerie Boyd, author of “Wrapped in Rainbows,” a biography about Hurston published in 2003.
The turn came in the 1980s.
Orange County authorities wanted to put a five-lane highway through the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the slow two-lane main street of the township.
Orlando’s suburbs had already pushed Highway 4 through the western outskirts of the city.
The proposal was made when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult phase in its history.
Forced integration, among other things, had put an end to the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the fight against racial mixing brought hatred to the community.
“At that time, a bunch of white boys often came and they threw oranges and stuff at the people sitting on the sidelines,” Mr. Franklin said.
“Once upon a time, there was a woman who was killed.
They threw a watermelon out of the car.”
In 1955, Hurston, in a letter to the Orlando Sentinel, questioned the Supreme Court’s demand to enforce integration, calling its decision in Brown’s case against the school council “insulting rather than respecting my race.”
Residents nowadays say that although the lifting of racial segregation was positive in some ways, it weakened group cohesion in Eatonville and the self-confidence of its youth.
"Black children were used to being hugged - I remember - they hugged their teacher in the morning and they hugged their teacher in the evening," said N. Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and executive director of the nonprofit group to protect the Eatonville community.
This could be maintained for so long, she added, until teachers and students no longer came from the same place.
“You didn’t hug your white teacher because he was a white teacher – I mean there’s a cultural divide there,” Ms. Nathiri said.
However, civil rights have helped make room for more Zora Neale Hurstons – black writers, actors, and artists who dismissed prejudices as she did, with positive self-confidence and statements like, “How can anyone refuse the joy of my society!
I don't understand."
In 1975, writer Alice Walker made her way to Hurston's nameless grave and began to fight for the revival of her fame.
Five years later, a much acclaimed Hurston biography of Robert E. Hemenway was found on the bookshelves, and again made it a part of the American literary canon.
The highway project came at a time when Eatonville’s most famous daughter was once again in the public eye.
And this time Hurston's old neighbors saw her as a savior.
The community began planning a Hurston festival in 1988 to show what the district could destroy with the construction of the highway.
Thousands of fans came to the opening event two years later, and every January many return for the celebration.
A few years later, the district turned away from its road construction plans.
“The plans of a five-lane highway revived the city, accelerated the whole thing at top speed, aroused real civil pride,” said Ms. Nathiri.
Ms. Boyd put it a little more simply: "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory against the highway project has contributed to a change in the self-image of the city.
There were more and more trainees, like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who has been going to church here since 1993, and locals began to re-appreciate the past.
Eatonville was added to the national historical register in 1998.
A new one-storey library (named after Hurston, of course) opened in 2006 on newly cobbled and beautified Kennedy Boulevard.
Nowadays, Eatonville is still a peculiarity in Florida: just 6 miles from downtown Orlando, it can sometimes feel like a back alley in summer rain, as small as it was when it was founded by only 27 black families in the 1880s.
(It’s 90% black nowadays.)
Outsiders looking for the history of Eatonville and its significance are often still treated with caution.
For most interviews, pre-approval is required and certain things – such as the wall painting of Eatonville’s oldest church, painted by a white man and depicting black men in the field – may not be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, such as Ms. Jones, a courageous, confident teacher with a fondness for dark red, still fear that their shielded community will be misunderstood.
And yet, at the same time that the Hurston Festival grew larger, an increased degree of homeland pride was also born.
Especially young people tend to see Eatonville as Hurston saw their entire race: beautiful, with all its problems, neither worse nor better, and just as proud, creative and diligent, silly and mixed up like any other racial and ethnic group in America.
It is the sincere love of this city that can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin’s nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, who plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in the city administration or the police, who might need some help, according to him.
And even the younger ones, like Alondra and Alexia Kenon, 11-year-old twins from Winter Park, have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Most people who just drive through here will think, 'Oh, this city is nothing compared to all the others,'" Alondra Kenon said the other day on a Sunday after church.
“But if you actually stop and look at its history for a moment, it’s a very beautiful city.”
Here in New York, we speak financial Latin fluently.
At first glance, nothing has changed.
If tourists in Manhattan kept away from the newspaper stands and the huge television screens in Times Square, they wouldn’t even notice that they were in the middle of a debacle.
They would never believe that over their heads, in the shoebox-like offices with the glass fa<0xC3><0xA7>ades, bankers and hedge fund managers who have the monopoly in New York, have the worst day of horror work every day since the 1929 stock market crash.
The suppliers still push the metal tea carts along pavements with loud clatter and carry trays loaded with muffins for the breakfast sessions.
Latinos still roam between apartments, like human pack animals loaded with around the 50 ironed T-shirts hanging on a yoke-like pole lying on their shoulders.
Office workers are still waiting for themselves on the sidewalks on their breakfast bagel and it is still impossible to get a yellow taxi on a weekday between 4pm and 7pm.
It didn’t feel like a crisis at all until I decided to open a new savings account on Thursday afternoon due to all the downfall of the world.
Although I had decided to put my compulsory course on the quiet late afternoon in my JP Morgan Chase branch, about 20 people were already in line.
Not at the cash desks to withdraw or deposit money, but at the customer service desk where regular customers order checkbooks, ask tourists about the way to the department store Macy's and where new customers open accounts.
Most before me, as I later learned from Starr, my "licensed personal bank employee", were for the same reason as I was in line.
However, unlike me, they had already withdrawn their savings from smaller banks, to places where they were commuting from, such as New Jersey, Pennsylvania, and Staten Island.
They had withdrawn money from so-called “thrifts” (a little like a construction bank), cooperative banks, and those local savings banks that only have branches in one state, saying they treat their customers like family.
Last year, 15 of these banks went quietly and quietly bankrupt.
In the last few days, Washington Mutual, a bank with $327 billion in assets, went bankrupt and when last Friday New Yorkers drove home over the weekend, Wachovia, another bank that owns $440 billion in savings, was looking for a saving buyer.
Fearful of another collapse, the office and store employees who were standing before me took their cash to a bank that is considered a safe harbor, a bank that is responsible for most of the rescue purchases on Wall Street.
Normal New Yorkers have acquired flowing financial Latino in recent weeks.
One woman, who was on the phone in my Chinese home supermarket, referred with so much familiarity to Lehman Brothers, the bankrupt bank, and their skinny-looking CEO Dick Fuld, as if she were slandering a lazy colleague.
And Lyn, the 50-year-old uniformed concierge of my apartment block, has diverted from our usual entertainment topics about Brad and Angelina and my grocery delivery.
"I now have all my savings in money market funds," she told me after my visit to the bank.
"I've changed, I'm not taking a risk anymore."
Muslim graves defiled during right-wing slide in Austria
Heinz-Christian Strache, a leftist of the Austrian right-wing Freedom Party, and Filip Dewinter, a member of the Belgian right-wing Pertei Vlaams Belang, take part in a demonstration in Antwerp on Thursday, January 17, 2008, to represent the organization "Cities against Islamization".
They carry signs in the style of traffic signs on which a mosque is depicted, crossed with a red line.
The police accuse right-wing extremists of desecration at a Muslim cemetery in Austria, the same weekend in which extreme right-wing parties recorded significant gains in the country's parliamentary election.
In the night from Friday to this morning, more than 90 graves in the cemetery in Traun near Linz were severely damaged in an organized action, according to police.
The perpetrators sprayed Jewish symbols such as the David Stern on some of the graves, but criminal officials believe this is an attempt to disguise the motive of extremists driven by hatred of Muslim immigrants.
It is not clear whether the incident is in any way related to the elections.
A spokesman for the local Islamic community said they were “deeply shaken” by the news of the grave desecration that took place as the religious month of Muslim Ramadan draws to a close.
At the same time, there is a round of conscience research in Austria after the country slipped to the right in yesterday’s parliamentary election.
The FPÖ and the Alliance for the Future of Austria, the two far-right parties that received almost 30% of the vote, campaigned for a strict anti-immigrant law in their election campaign and some of their voting rights were criticized by opponents as xenophobic.
Heinz-Christian Strache, chairman of the FPÖ, which won 18% of the vote, advocated a ban on headscarves and burqas, and even expressed his dislike for food commonly associated with Islam.
At his last rally in Vienna, he spoke of a “European brotherhood” to prevent the growth of Islam.
Both parties want to ban the construction of mosques and minarets with the argument that these political symbols are a continuous Islamization of Austria and Europe.
Surveys and analyses conducted immediately after the election, which say that the far right are the strongest political bloc in the country, suggest that this new development is based on young voters who are concerned about their future in the European Union.
