Drivers who may fall back due to alcohol levels will need to install the 'Alcolock'.
The authority orders that the driver, who had three official penalties for alcohol, installs this system in his car, which prohibits him from starting the car when drunk.
The initiative was announced last month in June and is already part of the report of the Attorney General’s Office. According to them, it is a pilot project, which will last for a year.
The purpose is to resocialize the driver, which is why he gets a course for re-education of traffic behavior.
In addition to the Attorney General's Office, experience has shown that the Ministry of Transport and the Foundation of the Technical Institute for the Safety of Automobiles will participate.
According to statistics, between 30-75% of drivers reported driving under the influence of alcohol more than once sat back at the wheel.
The 'alcolock' would prevent this because it is a system connected to the car, it measures the alcohol content in the exhaled air, and prevents car start when the driver has done alcohol testing; or if an alcohol concentration is found to be higher than is allowed.
It costs more than 1,000 euros, the cost is borne by the one who imposes the sanction.
In this context, a study conducted in the United States in 2007 showed that cars equipped with these devices prevent up to 65% of rule violations in the first year after its introduction.
In Spain, it is estimated that 115 lives could be saved each year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to tackle this behaviour before it becomes a crime.
And to facilitate its implementation, a lawful reform can be implemented in the ordinary way, and yet a reform of the Basic Law is called for, which is necessary for the prosecution process.
Still, the device is not available in the Spanish markets, in any store, although it has already been installed in some commercial vehicles and vehicles of public transport.
Tomorrow, the House of Representatives will vote on the initiative of the Spanish Socialist Workers' Party, which proposes to install this system in school buses, which has already been done in France.
