Conversation - The Blood That Became Safe Again
Hema-Quebec celebrated the 10th anniversary of its founding yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to be happy because Hema-Quebec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
Above all, it has regained public confidence, which had been severely shaken by the contaminated blood scandal of the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross blood donation service were contaminated with the HI virus and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this drama and public dissatisfaction, in February 1994, the Government of Canada launched a public inquiry, led by Judge Horace Krever, aimed at shedding light on the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy and drawing up guidelines to prevent a further disaster of this kind.
While Judge Krever was still hesitant to submit his report, several provinces at the time set up a committee whose goal was to develop a new system for managing blood preserves in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee carried out this task.
According to the reports of Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were established in Canada: Hema-Quebec, which is responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian Blood Society, to supply the other provinces and the two territories.
In 1998, when Hema-Quebec began its work, barely 38% of people had confidence in the blood preservative system in Quebec, Dr. Décary recalls.
The situation was discouraging.
“Through the tremendous efforts to improve the safety of blood preserves and by working in this area over the following years, we have regained public confidence,” she says, before proudly stressing that by the beginning of 2008, nearly 94% of Quebec’s population had confidence in Hema-Quebec.
However, Dr. Décary maintains that “trust is something extremely fragile.”
Since its inception on September 28, 1998, Hema-Quebec has acted on the principle of caution.
At that time, we witnessed the appearance of numerous cases of the human form of bovine madness in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, tells this woman, who has been in charge since 1998.
“And we had no idea if this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
So we referred to one of the main guidelines of the Krever and Gélineau reports, which states that exclusion measures are applied if one does not know this and if a disease progresses slowly, as is evidently the case with Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which manifests itself through a degeneration of the brain, which inevitably leads to death.
Thus, in April 1999, no blood was accepted from persons who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago, it was proven without any doubt that this disease is transmitted through the blood.
Thus, this event has shown us that the principle of caution that we have applied is quite meaningful.
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for the detection of HIV was released on the market: the nucleic acid tests (NST), which allow to detect the presence of the virus itself directly in the blood of the donor, and not that of the antibody against the virus, as was the case in the tests used so far.
The NST made it possible to shorten the incubation time, which takes place between the time the person was infected and when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, the specialist explains.
This time could be reduced to a duration of less than a week.
Thus, the risk that certain donors could be infected without knowing it, and one could not recognize it, was significantly reduced.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of transmitting AIDS through a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people is at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
In other words, it means that you would have to distribute 12 million blood cans before someone became infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 canned blood each year, it would take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission occurs through a canned blood.
I believe that nowadays you can feel comfortable getting a blood transfusion or prescribing it to restore health,” says the director of Hema-Quebec.
“Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen can enter the system.
It wasn’t until last year that the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted through the blood by insects.
We need to monitor continuously,' Dr. Décary continues, before she stresses that Hema-Quebec must also provide adequate supplies in addition to a safe supply.
“The demand is increasing because the population is aging.
Because cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population also affects the blood donor network, which on average accounts for only 3% of Quebec’s eligible blood donors.
Any healthy person who is 18 years of age or older and meets the fitness criteria can donate blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who provide their blood are not accepted because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and those who have traveled to a country where malaria is widespread will be excluded from donating blood for one year.
“With this 3%, we manage to get an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Lack of supplies is very rare.
But you have to renew the members of this donor network as they get older and can no longer donate blood.
It’s hard to convince people to donate blood, but most of all, to keep them and make them become regular donors.
Life is so hectic these days that you rarely find the time to spend an hour donating blood,” Francine Décary regrets.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Quebec delivers not only blood preserves, but also human tissue, including bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs and skin, which is used almost exclusively in severe fire injuries.
These tissues are examined, processed and frozen before being temporarily stored at Hema-Quebec, which also manages Quebec’s only public umbilical cord blood bank.
The umbilical cord, formerly considered biomedical waste, contains blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
<0x60>A few weeks ago we celebrated the storage of our thousandth umbilical cord blood sample, and we plan to lose more than a thousand annually.
“We should probably start making it available early next year for transplants,” explains Dr. Décary, who describes this program of cord blood removal as very popular.
“Many mothers are convinced they don’t have access to it,” because Hema-Quebec lacks the means to offer this complex and costly program in all Quebec hospitals.
