Free Opinion - The Orwellian Speech by Barrick Gold
In its September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, Deputy Director General of the Canadian Gold Mine Barrick Gold.
This confirms, and follows an Orwellian logic, that the world’s largest gold mining company sought a libel lawsuit of six million against three authors and a small destitute publishing house, with the aim of opening a ‘public transparent debate’.
If it is true that the judges are independent and impartial, then they do not judge on the truth, especially not in the case of slander lawsuits, but on the law.
As expected, this fundamental difference was completely obscured by Mr Garver.
For Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate is to ruin anyone who dares to represent one of their opposing opinions.
No matter how the process runs out, the authors and publishers of the book Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums to prepare their defense and fight with very unequal weapons against an army of lawyers paid from the almost inexhaustible pockets of the gold mine.
The tactic in these unequal struggles is, moreover, often to ruin the defenders in order to enforce a consensual arrangement that silences the opposing side and also deters anyone who dares to re-consider the issue.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, she would have had to present her view of things in front of public opinion.
Contrary to what is commonplace in many of the countries where Barrick Gold operates, debates in Canada are usually conducted by exchanging ideas rather than sticking.
So it would have been enough if the gold mine had unveiled its books and files and opened up a real debate through which newspapers, media, publications and the financing of independent audit teams could have shed light on this issue.
But Barrick Gold seems to have no confidence in public opinion and wipes out the petitions and letters in support of the authors of Noir Canada with a hand movement.
Could Mr Garver explain how he can ask for a 'public' debate at the same time and yet disregard the opinions of this very public?
Apparently, in the world of the Vice President, this word includes only the generously paid lawyers, and not the community of all Canadians; a rather narrow view of the term.
In a democracy, even slanderers have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold doesn’t understand – or doesn’t want to understand – is that the public that supports the authors and publishers of Noir Canada is doing so primarily because they reject the brutal stance of the gold mine.
This public is willing to listen to and judge Barrick, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, and not within a framework that many perceive as a gag lawsuit (in the course of the ‘public debate’ Barrick Gold has just addressed a demand to the authors of Noir Canada that they no longer use this term...).
Aside from Mr. Garver’s surreal speech, Barrick Gold’s lawsuit is a direct attack on the freedom of academic research and truth-finding that is fundamental to any democratic society.
It completely denies the right to cite credible sources and to discuss facts and interpretations that form the basis of intellectual work.
If in a country like Canada it is impossible to explore and discuss issues that the rich companies of this world do not like, who else can do that?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, she could lead it by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Noir Canada.
She has a right to answer.
The university environment to which we belong has long been able to cope with debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold’s disproportionate lawsuit clearly shows that, contrary to what it pretends, it does not want a transparent debate.
This is a loss for the university world, as well as for the public debate, and it is time for governments to take action to curb this type of unjustified lawsuit.
Wall Street Rescue: Democrats and Republicans Agree
The Bush administration and senior congressmen, Republicans and Democrats alike, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the most comprehensive economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion plan to stop the financial crisis that has been shaking Wall Street for months has yet to be adopted by the two chambers of Congress.
The main contents are: better control of MEPs over the practical application of the plan, new mechanisms to secure the repayment of the public funds used, new provisions to curb the number of houses seized due to arrears, as well as the right to monitor the salaries paid to the executives of the supported companies.
U.S. Secretary of Finance Henry Paulson, Speaker of the House of Representatives Nancy Pelosi, and Republican Rep. Senator Judd Gregg announced the good news yesterday, minutes after midnight, after a two-day marathon.
“We have made great strides towards an agreement that will be market-effective,” said Bush administration representative Henry Paulson.
“Everything was done to protect the real economy and the American people from the price crisis on Wall Street,” she said.
“This is the fundamental point: if we don’t do that, the trauma, the chaos and the unrest in the daily lives of Americans will be enormous,” said Republican Judd Gregg.
Negotiations had accelerated over the past two hours, fearing the impact that a further failure would have had on the mood of investors.
The deadline that had been agreed was the market opening this morning.
The two U.S. presidential candidates, who were late in the negotiations, were more likely to support the agreement, but without failing to express their dissatisfaction with the need to meet them in this extreme way.
Democratic Senator Barrack Obama insisted on the addition of certain injunctions to the agreement, especially those that should allow owners to keep their homes, and those that concern the salaries of the executives of the companies rescued by the state.
“If you ask taxpayers to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of certain people, that is not something to be congratulated on.
But these measures are necessary," he said on American television.
When asked on another station if he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent John McCain replied: “I’d like to know the details first, but I hope so.
“The guidelines I have read [show] that this is one thing that we will all have to digest, and with which we will be able to move forward.
The option of doing nothing is simply not acceptable,” he said.
The $700 billion plan is geared towards taxpayers’ money.
It comes 14 months after a crisis triggered by the bursting of a real estate bubble that initially led to the collapse of high-risk mortgages (subprimes) before expanding to other forms of more widespread bonds (PCAAs), and eventually led to a freezing of financial strength and the ruin of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of Republican MPs who failed last week’s first attempt at an agreement.
Since the Democrats have accepted that certain "toxic" assets of societies in distress should only be secured by the government and not bought, it is believed that they escape the dead end.
To round off the viewpoints for everyone in Congress, an order has also been added that if the government were to make losses with this program within five years, it could then levy new taxes in order to regain its capital used.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first sum of $250 billion, to which another $100 billion can be added if the president deems it necessary.
The payment of another $350 billion must be approved in a new vote by Congress.
In return for his help, Washington receives shares in the supported companies, which will pay him dividends in the event of profits, and which it can sell back when the storm has passed.
The Federal Government will have the option of stopping the garnishment procedures for the apartments linked to the real estate loans affected by this plan, as well as setting deadlines for repayment and compensation to be paid to the senior employees of the companies concerned.
The developers of the plan would like the Chamber of Deputies to vote on it today, and the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all her efforts, it is not yet certain that her plan will get a green light.
In fact, more votes were raised yesterday against this project, both on the part of the Republicans and the Democrats.
“Obviously Washington doesn’t understand us,” Republican Scott Garett, a member of the House Financial Committee, told voters.
“Yes, we have a big financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not the one that consists in asking the taxpayers to pay the tax.”
Democratic Rep. Brad Sherman, head of a group in Congress called the “Caucus of Skeptics,” represents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
“Four hundred distinguished economic professors, including three Nobel laureates, have written to us to let us know: we ask Congress not to be put under pressure and to carefully consider which path to take,” he said yesterday.
At the same time, we in Europe once again received proof that this is a global crisis.
At an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the Fortis banking group for 11.2 billion euros ($16.3 billion).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it would refrain from buying its competitor, who is in great difficulty since it lost 2 billion euros ($2.9 billion) in the crisis due to the risky real estate loans in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of the 20 largest European banks and the 10 largest insurers.
"This is not lost money," Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
To compensate, we get a right to vote and influence in the bank.
This is exactly what savers and households appreciate now that uncertain times are looming.”
During this time, on the other side of the English Channel, the British government was just about to nationalize another bank brought into distress by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would take over all ongoing loans at Bank Bradford and Bringley, including over 41 billion ($75.5 billion) from real estate loans.
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it would buy up the branches and customer accounts of the British bank.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank to be nationalized by the British government since the beginning of this financial crisis.
Paul Newman (19252008) - Death of a dedicated icon
His beauty with the azure eyes was for a long time his trump, nobody would say his weakness.
Had the American actor freed himself from the narcissistic mirror with the charming smile?
Yes and no.
His sensitivity, sensitivity and obvious talent have probably kept him away from a position of power that gives birth to the truly terrible monsters.
But what a great continuous runner!
Paul Newman, who died on Friday at the age of 83 from lung cancer on his ranch in Connecticut, remains one of the last American cinema icons of his golden years.
He was less monumental than Brando, to whom he resembled and for whom he was for a long time a kind of rival on the canvas, more careful in his spectacle, certainly also more fragile, but just as an apostle of freedom and the blowing up of dramatic conventions.
Mixed blood often produces wonderful children.
He was born in 1925 in Ohio as the son of a German Jew and a Hungarian-born mother.
From his European roots one of the glorious faces of the American dream was to emerge.
Without excessive ego, extreme quality feature.
Because in him a whole country that was in love with the self-made man was reflected, in the fighter who was injured in the war in the Pacific, who studied acting art in Yale in the early 1950s and then visited the Actor's Studio in New York before he had success in theater, television and soon also in cinema.
This man, who fought for civil rights, was also the driver who became second in the 1979 24-hour race of Mans, and also a sex symbol, although he lived together with actress Joanne Woodward since 1958 in a showcase relationship.
With him also disappear the unknown facets of this mysterious, reserved, committed and hypersensitive star to the glamour of the show business, whose riddles can never be solved completely.
A decent man, in the purest sense of the word.
The death of Paul Newman put movie lovers in a mood this weekend, while all his great roles were played on the dark screen of memories.
More than half a century of ever-changing American film art passes by with him.
Then again the charming cowboy from Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid (1969) comes to mind, and the young man who rejects his sensual wife (Elizabeth Taylor) in The Cat on the Hot Sheet Metal Roof, which was filmed by Tennessee Williams in 1958.
A much shorter memory (1990) is awakened to his sensitive Mr. Bridge, who at his old age is disturbed by a wedding that did not fulfill all her promises.
There have been so many other Paul Newmans throughout history.
This criminal, stormy, violent and unforgettable boxer Rocky Graziano from Somebody Up There Likes Me by Robert Wise, a role intended for James Dean, who was reprised after his death and made the Newman famous in 1956.
This sympathetic Ganove in the outstanding The Sting (The Clou), who was awarded the Oscar for best film in 1973.
A fierce and vengeful billiard player in Robert Rossen’s The Hustler (1961).
That face through the ages, that was him.
Still him.
In his résumé, epochs unite.
The youth know him most from the cult film Slap Shot by George Roy Hill (1977), as Reggie Dunlop, the unorthodox coach of an ice hockey team.
His fans found him again in 1994 in The Hudsucker Proxy of the Coen Brothers.
With a final role in 2003 as the godfather of the Irish mafia in Road to Perdition by Sam Mendes, the circle closed.
Unlike several movie legends who retired early enough from the film world, Newman was supposed to stay in the saddle for a long time, betraying Hollywood, his fortune, his pomp and his concessions.
The French filmmaker Bertrand Tavernier saw him, not without humor, as a living challenge to ‘underplaying’ when he judged his overly expressive achievements.
It wasn’t always easy for the handsome Paul Newman, to whom the roles flew for a long time.
However, he played less often Sunnyboys than outsiders: neurotics, alcoholics, bastards or the desperate, with whose perfect representation he reflected his slippage and his rebellion.
As a director, Newman revealed unknown sides of his true sensitive sensibility.
His 1968 novel Rachel, based on the Canadian novel Margaret Laurence, starring his wife Joanne Woodward, drew a subtle portrait of women full of melancholy.
He, who lost his son Scott to an overdose, dedicated his 1984 film Harry and Son, a work of sensitivity and sadness.
In the flood of honors that erupted over Newman yesterday, his close friend and former comrade in arms Robert Redford (they had played together in The Sting and Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid) said: "His presence has improved my life and this country."
Generosity and joie de vivre were essential characteristics of the deceased actor.
Aside from his legendary career, a great advocate of civil rights, environmental protection and independent cinema, an opponent of Hollywood’s drift, is now going there.
We have probably often seen him stand with his foot in bowls full of vinaigrette, in sauces, pastries or other foods, and thought this was quite tasteless, although we still found it funny at first.
The profits from his sales nevertheless flowed into his foundation for children in need.
Instead of resting on his myth, Newman engaged himself to the point of being shot.
He left a letter to his five daughters with these sentences: “Always and to the end, your father was incredibly grateful for his good star.
It was an honor to be here.”
And it was an honor for us to be able to follow the life of such an intelligent and generous American actor.
An exemplary citizen, in the narrowest and broadest sense.
What was produced in the invoice factory of Zuschlag &amp; Co.?
On October 8, negotiations begin in the criminal trial against János Zuschlag and his accomplices.
In particular, the accused are accused of involvement in organized crime, as well as grossly negligent harm and business fraud, and other criminal acts, including falsification of documents.
According to the prosecutor's office, the funds lucrated from the tenders were used for their own purposes, while the services provided were often documented with fake invoices.
State funds and grants from the self-government - a total of HUF 65 million - are supposed to have flowed partly into the coffers of the organization Fiatal Baloldal, partly into the private coffers of individuals.
As the investigative authorities announced, when obtaining the tender money, fictitious invoices were submitted, and the clubs should not have fulfilled their obligations.
According to the indictment, a large part of the bills were counterfeited.
The bill blocks were bought at the Józsefváros market, the round seals were made in Kiskunhalas.
The decision on which companies to issue the invoices was made on that round trip north of Lake Balaton, to which István Lados was sent by János contract.
In the course of this "exploration tour" Lados should find pensions and restaurants.
He demanded consumption invoices in order to be able to issue invoices for the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labour, and the Budapest self-government.
The majority of these bills are said to have been manipulated by István Lados and his accomplice, András <0xC5><0x90>ri, who, according to our information, was responsible for the constitution of the corresponding reports.
One of the destinations of Lados' "exploration tour" was a beer restaurant.
As can be seen from two invoices issued by Zuschlag and Co in 2003, the catering company is said to have hosted the ninety-member group of the association Biztos Pont Egyesület.
Now, however, the head of the company states that such a large group would not have fit into the restaurant at once.
Another bill, issued in the summer of 2002 to the Jobb Jöv<0xC5><0x91>ért Foundation, later known as Együtt a Harmadik <0xC3><0x89>vezredért, also showed serious errors in form and content.
