The Psychology of Overbidding – Or Why We Are Ready to Pay More
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more and thus overvalue the bid.
Neurologists and economic researchers at the University of New York have now succeeded in discovering the neurological-economic foundations of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in the "Science" magazine, people don't want to give up in a competition, such as an auction on eBay, and are therefore willing to pay even excessive prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers was to play lottery while the other participated in a playful action - in both cases the subjects' active brain regions were examined using functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI).
In both games, participants were able to win money, but increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the brain bark, was measured in auction losers, in which overbidding the opponent plays a significant role.
In addition to many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self-reward" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore thought that the price increase could be explained by avoiding an overreaction of the striatum.
In order to support their thesis, the economists in the research group have additionally carried out investigations to track the money.
In this case, three groups should compete against one partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product, after which they made their bets.
Another group was also promised a $15 reward in case they emerged as winners from the game.
The third group received $15 before the auction, which was also lost in the event of a lost game.
The difference between the two groups was that the emphasis on the one was on winning, while the other was on losing.
As proof of the hypothesis expressed by neurologists, however, the members of the "against losing" group were willing to higher stakes than those in the control or "win" group.
“These results cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
These have justified the behaviours observed at auctions so far only with the joy of winning or avoiding risk.
The contradiction between these two theories was resolved thanks to imaging neurological procedures, so we now have a third explanation ready," said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When to see the doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed as one of the leading causes of death.
The number of infected people is estimated at one hundred thousand in this country, but only seven thousand are treated, which is because patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for infectious liver disease caused by various viruses.
The symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and jaundice are common, but the pathogens and diseases differ.
Depending on the pathogen, the hepatitis viruses spread in two different ways: in hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (for example, contaminated food or water), in hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted through blood and other body fluids (such as sperm, vaginal secretion or saliva).
Travellers are recommended to vaccinate against viruses A and B, in any case, there is no vaccine against virus C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A occur about two to three weeks after consuming the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by discomfort, weakness, abdominal pain, and nausea.
Afterwards, the jaundice occurs on the skin and in the eyes, the stool becomes light, the urine dark, and recovery can take up to two-three weeks.
Around 1 million people worldwide die each year from the much more serious diseases caused by hepatitis B, such as liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten people infected is on drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: untreated it can lead to liver cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, as the pathogen insidiously destroys the liver cells - in many cases, the first symptoms show up after 20-30 years.
Timely prevention, such as regular inspections, is therefore essential.
There are three groups in which this disease is more common: those who underwent a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattooists.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide is estimated at 200 million.
