As recent research shows, religious belief acts as a kind of “pain medicine” that is said to have already facilitated the death of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University have conducted an interesting experiment: It has been studied to what extent faith in God influences human pain, the British newspaper Telegraph reported.
In the course of the rather bizarre investigation, 12 believers and atheists each received electroshocks while studying a painting of the Mother of God.
As the results showed, the believers were able to eliminate most of the pain.
By means of a brain scan technology, it could even be demonstrated that the Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain that is responsible for pain regulation.
The study was the first in a research project involving scientists, philosophers and theologians from various departments of the university.
During the test, a sparkling device was attached to the left hand, which gave off the electroshocks.
Participants were asked to focus strongly on two paintings: on the one hand a picture of the Mother of God, painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century, and on the other hand Leonardo da Vinci's "Lady with the Hermelin".
The researchers hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary would provoke a kind of religious trance among the faithful, while choosing da Vinci’s image, because it was hardly different from the other painting and felt as reassuring.
The subjects each spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and received a total of 20 electroshocks in four stages during this time, while they were to view either the religious or the other painting.
The Catholics reported that they felt “safe” at the sight of the Mother of God, as if they were “cared for” and felt “rest and peace.”
While viewing the religious painting, they reported about 12% less pain than when they had Leonardo’s work in mind.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the experiment, said that you could also evoke similar effects with other, powerful images also among the atheists, you just had to find the corresponding photo.
"We would have to find an image that triggers very positive feelings, like a mother or a father," he said.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
“Practicing faith should change our personality, and it does in many cases,” Wright said.
