Intelligent car imitates the flight of the bumblebee
What would be the best way to develop new technologies for accident prevention, if not to imitate the obstacle sensors from nature?
For example, the bees.
At CEATEC in Japan, an amazing project was presented that inspired bumblebee’s Nissan engineers to create new accident-preventing systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the BR23C auto-robot-controlled biomimetic system, a mini-car equipped with the characteristics of bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collisions.
In flight, each bee forms its own oval “private area”, which is very similar to our own “protection shield”, Kazuhhiro Doi, product manager for technology PR and research development, said at the exhibition.
The composite eye of the bee, which can see in any direction and at an angle of over 300 degrees, plays an important role.
In order to mimic the function of the composite eye, the researchers took up the idea of the laser-controlled distance meter.
It identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C in a 180-degree field of view within 2 meters, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor on board, which immediately initiates the collision-preventing process.
The obstacle is recorded in fractions of a second, and the auto robot immediately changes the course, similar to the movement of the bees, by rotating the tires at the appropriate angle.
Unlike previous systems, this maneuver takes place purely instinctively.
“If it weren’t, the robotic vehicle wouldn’t be able to react quickly enough to avoid the obstacles,” said Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the Robotic Vehicle Project.
The system must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the innermost and most vulnerable part of the shield - a layer within which accidents are currently still considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect the behavior of the bees when they dodge other bees.
And that has to happen in a fraction of a second.
However, the avoidance, unlike the bees, can not take place up, down, or even diagonally - it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction of the reversibility of the tires.
While there are infinite possibilities for the bees to avoid other bees, the researchers could only use rotary motion, or acceleration and deceleration, in the auto robot.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and more energy efficient, and therefore have a longer lifespan than conventional lithium-ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it depends on the instinctive, intelligent response, and less on the processing of the data, and even less on the ability to store it.
This device only needs to process a few inputs per second and respond to them accordingly.
It does not have to store them or produce an intuitive, logical response from previous maneuvers, so it only requires a handful of KB of memory.
There is no need for gigabyte and megabyte of memory.
This is the first step in the development of the immediate collision avoidance technology, which Nissan estimates will be in production within the next ten years.
Another application could find the technology in GPS satellite navigation by consciously steering the driver around obstacles and thus guiding him to the destination.
