Despite the electoral debacle, no heads are rolling at the moment, at the head of the Bavarian CSU the personnel debates were postponed.
Party leader Erwin Huber and Prime Minister Beckstein remain in their posts, the question is only how long this grace lasts.
The fate of the tandem after the catastrophic loss of 17 percent of the vote will be decided on the last weekend of October at the extraordinary party congress.
The much reviled duo, however, already showed that it does not want to stick on their armchairs.
With this they want to appease the annoyed faction and the party base, which one day after the "Bavarian tsunami" demanded personal consequences in the face of the loss of the absolute majority.
Five years ago - admittedly, under the leadership of Edmund Stoiber, who was at the peak of his career - the Christian Social Union still reached 60.7 percent, but now, a year after the coup against Stoiber, they were only able to secure 43.4 percent of the votes.
For 46 years, the CSU was a “single-ruler” in Bavaria, which generates 18 percent of German GDP.
Although the Conservatives remain the determining force in the southern federal state, which is also important for the Hungarian economy, they will have to govern in a coalition in the future.
As the first sign of the party internal restructurings, the potential successor of Huber, Vice President and Federal Minister of Agriculture Horst Seehofer will also be involved in the exploration team, which leads exploratory talks with the liberal FDP or the right-wing "free voters" about a possible Munich coalition.
It is an irony of fate that with the list of “free voters”, Gabriele Pauli enters the legislature, whose anti-stoipers first used the Huber-Beckstein Duo in order to mercilessly dismiss the determined politician.
The CSU leadership is now concentrating all its forces on the stabilization of Beckstein.
Stoiber, who has so far pulled the strings out of the background, is playing an active role in this transition process, calling 28 September the "bitterest day of his political career".
On Monday, Huber made a few poisonous remarks towards the CDU - in his opinion, the CSU deserved far more support from the sister party.
Other CSU politicians interpreted the defeat as a signal to the CDU and thus also to Angela Merkel.
If the CSU, which also contributed much to success at the national level in 2005, is not put back on its feet with a joint act of force, Merkel cannot become Chancellor again after the Bundestag elections in September 2009.
Merkel, who has made no secret of her disappointment at the fiasco, believes that the loss of CSU terrain will not have a negative impact on the great coalition in Berlin.
What is relative, however, is that the wounded CSU will not be easier to govern, and the crisis of the Social Democrats continues.
With 18.6 percent, the SPD achieved its best result so far in Bavaria since 1946.
Lukashenko opposition: 110-0
In the elections on Sunday, no opposition MP was able to enter the Ukrainian parliament.
Russian observers believe this is due to prosperity and stability in the country led by Alexander Lukashenko, but the OECD suspects illegal counting of votes.
The OECD, which sent 450 observers from 43 countries, did not recognize the elections.
Although the legislature of the 10-million-strong state has been without opposition for decades, the opposing party, which has gathered under the name "Unified Democratic Forces" (ODS) before yesterday's elections, earnestly hoped that Lukashenko, who in the unclean elections and thanks to a constitutional amendment in 2006, would "release some of the president's mandate" for the fourth time.
That is why the ODS has even distanced itself from the previously planned boycotts.
Ukraine is becoming more and more economically dependent thanks to the rising prices on the import of natural gas from Russia. For the alleviation of the price increases, even loans have been taken, and the country has also agreed to the sale of Beltransgas, the owner of the gas pipeline leading by the country, to the Russians. So in the background of the expectations of the opposition there was the hope that the Ukraine would improve its relationship with the EU because of the anti-political opposition.
A temporary relaxation was provided by the OECD’s election evaluation report, in which the emphasis was on the positive moves rather than the shortcomings – such as the exclusion of a third of the opposition candidates from the elections.
However, the OECD's rapid report criticized the campaign - according to which opposition members are not expected to appear in the press - and in particular the fact that the opposition was not allowed to be present in the counting of the votes.
Despite all this, the opposition is able to see an improvement in the political system: political prisoners have been set free, for example, and Minsk is even ready for minor confrontations with Moscow by continuing to deny recognition of the independence of the apostate Georgian provinces of South Ossetia and Abkhazia, although Russia, with which Ukraine on paper forms an independent federal state, has considered the two territories as a month.
“We have taken two steps forward and one step backward, but the most important thing is that the dialogue between Belarus and the EU has begun,” Milinkevich told our newspaper.
According to the opposition candidate of the 2006 presidential election, a continuation is desirable, although "the powerful have been afraid to leave even one oppositional in parliament".
The opposition does not plan protests in the light of the results, but rather tries to make the need for economic reform clear to the voters.
"We are struggling here with many problems - the opposition newspapers have to be printed in Russia, the local authorities are putting us in the way of distributing stones, but nevertheless I see that more and more people are supporting the change, even the older ones," Milinkevich said, referring to the fact that not even the most supported stratum of pensioners agrees with the Lukashenko regime, whose only safety is production.
“Thanks to the country’s indebtedness and the increase in the trade deficit, it is only a matter of time before the ‘social security’ warning the silence of a cemetery begins to crumble,” Milinkevich said.
In contrast to opposition politicians, Russian observers have called the elections democratic.
Sergey Lebedev, head of the mission of the Commonwealth of Independent States, told the Ria Novosti news agency: "People believe in deeds, not words." The lack of opposition is therefore proof of the maturity of Belarusian voters.
