Napolitano: "Prevention of accidents at work is crucial"
Every day in Italy 2,500 accidents occur at work, three people die and 27 remain disabled for life.
For the year 2007, the data of the Inail (Istituto nazionale contro gli infortuni sul lavoro) confirm that the fatal accidents at work were around 1200.
These figures prove the seriousness of a phenomenon that causes almost twice as many deaths as murders.
Today, the Anmil (Associazione Nazionale Mutilati e Invalidi del Lavoro) will celebrate the 58th National Day for Victims of Work Accidents in all the provinces of Italy, in order to draw the attention of social institutions and media to this dramatic situation.
"The worrying data disseminated by Anmil and the tragic news of these days confirm how crucial the issue of prevention in the workplace is," confirmed the President of the Republic Giorgio Napolitano in his communication to the President of the Amil (Associazione nazionale mutilati ed invalidi del lavoro) Pietro Mercandelli.
The head of state expresses his "great appreciation for the constant commitment to prevention in the workplace, to the protection of injured workers, to aid the families of the victims and to raise awareness of public opinion".
"An outraged 'Basta' has arisen on this; understandable in tragedies that, in terms of their magnitude, trigger some vortices in the media and participation of the public. But the everyday reality often confronts us with dramatic events that can even be repeated in their own dynamics."
Napolitano does not hide that "there is definitely also a resource problem: it must be invested decisively in education and information."
The numerous initiatives for a more direct awareness in school settings by young people who feed on the world of work are of particular importance.
It is our duty to focus attention on this phenomenon and not to distract from its social seriousness. A legislative norm must be put in place and improved.
For his part, the President of the Chamber Gianfranco Fini stressed "how the phenomenon of work-related deaths constitutes an urgent social emergency that offends the conscience of all of us and forces all institutions to work towards decisive rules that aim to put an end to the problem".
"The data on workplace accidents seem to signal a slight improvement, but this does not exclude that the number of work-related deaths is far too high," emphasizes Anmil President Pietro Mercandelli.
"We don't want this 'positive tendency' to mean less attention. That's what causes the tragedy in the end."
"How do you think that you are basically doing too little to counter the phenomenon of accidents? You can fight it through various actions.
In our opinion, stronger controls and inspections are necessary – according to Mercandelli; but also stronger measures to educate the workers who are already starting out in school.
"Another effort is necessary - he adds - in terms of communication and awareness of public opinion.
But above all, a greater sense of responsibility on the part of employers towards a phenomenon that represents a social emergency is required.
Mercandelli also spoke of the "progressive deterioration of the protection of victims of accidents at work" and denounced the "abolition of the social system that we have been fighting against in recent years".
The aim is therefore to provide the worker with a guarantee on insurance, so that the fate of the victim of an accident at work does not become dependent on voluntary or random donations, which are decided from time to time by a legislature.
MP3 Player Under Charge: Risk of Hearing Damage
Listening to loud music over a longer period of time using portable music devices, such as MP3 players, can lead to permanent hearing impairment.
This is reported by the European Commission, which in a report published today in Brussels quotes the opinion of the EU’s Csrseri (scientific committee on current and recently identified health risks).
“It is clear from the report that 5-10% of those who listen to loud music with portable music devices for at least five years a week for more than an hour a day are at risk of permanent hearing loss.”
"I'm worried that such a large number of young people, who usually turn on portable music devices and mobile phones at a high volume, will irretrievably damage their hearing without knowing it," said Meglena Kuneva.
"From the scientific findings - it is said on the part of the EU - there is a clear risk that urges rapid action.
What really matters is to raise awareness among consumers and to make this information a communal asset.
In the light of these scientific findings, we need to re-examine the existing control systems so that they are fully effective and keep up with the new technology."
Brussels had commissioned the independent scientific committee in view of the widespread use of portable music devices among young people.
"The scientists - this is the conclusion of the EU communication - confirm that one is rightly concerned and that the EU Commission, together with the other EU Members and those concerned, will now examine the necessary measures to be able to better protect children and young people from the noise coming from portable music devices and similar devices."
There is already a European standard that limits the level of noise from portable music devices to 100 dB. The concern about the damage that could come from too much noise.
These damages can be very limited by resorting to solutions such as the reduction of the volume and the length of the noise setting.
In its report, the scientific committee of the EU points out that if users of portable music devices only listen to loud music five hours a week (more than 89 decibels) so that the legal limits that apply to the maximum noise level at the workplace are already exceeded.
Those who cross this line of music risk complete hearing loss within five years.
This is 5-10% of the users of such devices, whose number can be estimated at between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
Roma, Alemanno gives the start of the "Commission for the future of the capital"
We're starting today, it's supposed to be over in March, we're going to take stock in June.
This is the procedure laid down by the Capitol for the work of the Commission for the Future of the Capital of Rome, which met this morning at the new headquarters behind the Caracalla Baths.
In six months, President Marzano and the other 49 members of the Commission will draw up the guidelines for Rome.
Once the project is completed, the City Council and the City Council will evaluate the analyses and projects in order to be able to present the strategic plan for Rome in June with the "official stamp" of the Capitol and Mayor Gianni Alemanno.
"The Commission is absolutely independent and all political, social and cultural opinions are represented in it", - stresses Alemanno. "It will present proposals for a development plan for Rome, whose political responsibility remains with the City Council and the Municipal Council.
There is no reallocation of responsibilities, only the will to have a place where one can develop a great project for Rome.
In March, its task will be completed and the Commission will dissolve again, as such a project must have a certain end point in time.
In June, the mayor announced, we will present the strategic plan in which we will use the work done by the Commission."
If you question the Commission's competence because of its lack of commitment, Alemanno replies: "It all depends on the work that the Commission will do and the quality of its proposals.
If, as in France, the Attali Commission delivers quality results – and this will certainly be the case in Rome – then their contribution will be fundamental.
Too often, politics deals with the everyday problems and emergencies that occur from time to time.
We, on the other hand, want to have a longer period of time in mind in order to work seriously on the development of Rome and the future of the city in a deeper perspective.”
"This commission is neither a useless institution nor a wreck: it is absolutely free, it will not cost the Roman citizens a penny and it will make us think, it will employ the best minds of the capital".
According to Alemanno, “it is necessary to have a strategic plan that is neither hermetic nor static to enable our city to make a leap in quality – which it really needs – and thus to take a joint step into the future.”
A future, according to the mayor of Rome, which "will not only limit itself within the current municipal boundaries, but will look much further", not only with regard to the role of Rome as a metropolis and political capital of Italy, but also as the future capital of Europe and the Mediterranean."
