The elite is in danger.
The phenomenon had already been revealed a few days ago when the House of Representatives voted against the $700 billion savings package of the White House: a large part of Americans were and are more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
This is confirmed by yesterday’s issue of the New York Times, which reports how the ongoing crisis is dividing the Republican Party, which is increasingly splitting into its old and moderate East Coast soul, which has always favored state institutions and the business community, and those neoconservatives who are hostile to “those in Washington” and the financial world, and especially the central and central states.
This part of the party owes its rise above all to the voice of the one I mentioned above.
This example just mentioned, however, is only a small part of the major changes that the current economic earthquake heralds or even represents already: not only in the United States, but also throughout the West and perhaps beyond, will be affected by these.
Both in the states and in Europe, the crisis seems to accelerate the long-feared events, which are finally taking shape and coming to light under these new conditions.
The first of these phenomena is the rediscovery, the unprecedented renaissance of the state in conjunction with a kind of renationalization of the economy.
Indeed, the crisis means a decline in the banking and financial institutions, which have close ties to foreign countries and at the same time manage a tremendous amount of the assets of private households residing in a single state.
This represents an immediate political problem for governments: namely, how to behave towards the families concerned, which are also an enormous mass of voters.
The crisis thus appears economically global, but politically it is almost purely national.
Political internationalism seems to have fallen into disrepair and lost its right to speak: the EU, which, due to its division into various national and international conflicts, does not know how to find a common way.
Therefore, everyone now expects the intervention of their own state; rescue plans, new rules, and above all distribution of aid funds: since the crisis became more serious, only the US is in the economic situation to save itself without foreign help.
And in addition to the means, they also have the legitimacy to use them: thus two not to be overestimated prerequisites – under certain circumstances – to which otherwise no international organization or market will be able to resort in a similar way.
This new emphasis, which is placed on the national-state element, is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the ever-increasing importance that has recently been associated in the economy with a closely related sector: territoriality.
Paradoxically, just now, when we were so convinced that we had long since entered a networked world, a world of ever-differentiated technologies, of the immaterial, we must at once determine how our future will depend more and more on the essential material things: water, harvest and oil.
Although they can all be transported from one place in the world to another, they are still connected to a narrowly defined piece of earth – a territory.
Hence, the person who has such a territory is in favour of another who lives in a land free of oil or water or in a land without crop yields.
I now come to the second novelty, which, however, requires a brief introduction.
Whoever says territory, whoever says government, whoever says politics, whoever says leadership.
In this sense, the financial crisis seems to generate two convergent phenomena.
On the one hand, there is the knowledge of the need for respected leadership, that is, the need for someone who knows how to manage things.
On the other hand, there is now a wave of indignation over the existing leaderships, especially those of the economy, which have turned out to be insufficient and full of shadow zones.
Finally, there is a deeper and in a sense still troubling aspect: a loss of trust, a lack of patience, an image of inconvenience, a feeling of distance, all directed at a whole class of managers of Western countries.
It seems that the conviction among large sections of the population that it is not only the deeds of the social elite, but already their world of ideas, their way of life, their culture in the broadest sense of the word, whose salary is represented by the majority as becoming more foreign and more outdated.
The demand for leadership, therefore, subterraneanly nurtures a branched but powerful movement of the disempowerment of the leading class and the traditional political establishment, manifested in the unforeseen "revolts" of the voters and in the sudden change of the right of the collective state of mind of recent times, perhaps by the United States of America (beginning with the rise of the conservatives in Germany and the United States of America).
One gets the impression that the old elite, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, magazines, intellectual creditors, some would say their format, have more and more problems of understanding and therefore less representative value with regard to what is happening today in the lower social strata of the West and is further reinforced and pushed by the financial crisis to superdimensionality.
In view of all this, it would simply be exaggerated to speak of a “rebellion of the masses”.
Keeping your eyes wide open is certainly not.
The super glue that goes up on walls
Defeat the forces of gravity thanks to an adhesive and be able to climb walls like Superman.
This is the subject of four American research centers, one of which has now apparently almost reached its destination.
With an adhesive applied on an area of only 2.5 square centimeters, the researchers have succeeded in fixing a 100 kg body on a vertical wall.
The STUDIO – an American journal has published the results of researchers from the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material invented by the research team is a further development of the adhesives already in use, which use a special carbon structure, called carbon nanotubes.
“The principle of glue can be imagined as a row of spaghetti tubes arranged in a stack,” explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
Scientists have been inspired by the geckos’ feet, which are covered by microscopic hairs that give the animal a perfect hold.
Tests using various materials, such as glass teflon and sandpaper, have shown that the new adhesive is ten times stronger than the ability of reptile feet to hold and at the same time "easily remove from the wall," said Liming Dai, a researcher at the University of Dayton's Faculty of Engineering.
"This material could be used as a perishable adhesive," adds Liming Dai.
Maybe it is, but the researchers are thinking of a less fascinating benefit, such as connecting electrical devices, because the nanotubes are also conductors of heat and electricity.
Further applications could fall into the field of space travel.
For now, the superheroes have to wait.
THE OTHER WAY OF RESEARCH – including the University of Berkeley, California, is dedicated to a new kind of adhesive.
In an article by the American Chemical Society, California scientists present an adhesive made of microfibers that cleans itself from dust by moving like hair on a surface, always maintaining perfect adhesion.
Medicines: never take with fruit juice
Beware of grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, which are consumed especially in summer due to their refreshing quality and vitamin richness, can cause serious health damage when taken with certain vital drugs, as they can have an extreme effect on the absorption of these by the body.
At the 236th meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia, David Bailey, a professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, repeatedly points out the risk of packaging and fresh fruit juices associated with taking medication. He again raised the alarm that a glass of apple, orange or grapefruit juice is enough to reduce the absorption capacity of certain vital medicines and to reduce the health of patients.
Grapefruit juice was already suspected to be responsible for increasing the effects of some drugs such as antibiotics, anti-asthma drugs, cardiovascular drugs, anxiolytic and neurological agents, up to toxic levels.
In a report two years ago, the same drug agency warned doctors and patients of the dangers of this mixture, and stressed that they should be careful about what is being drunk in conjunction with drugs such as diazepam or methadone.
It’s not just a GRAPHIC – according to experts, orange juice and apple juice also contain substances that can inhibit the drugs.
The list of active ingredients inhibited by fruit juices is long.
Michele Carruba, director of the Universit<0xC3><0xA0> Statale di Milano, said: "Such results are usually immediately forwarded to the various international manufacturers who are free to change consumer information.
Therefore, it is advisable to always read the package leaflet and, if there are still ambiguities, do not be afraid to ask a pharmacist or doctor, "emphasizes the expert of the Ansa agency.
Nobel Prize goes to Paul Krugman
The Nobel Prize in Economics is awarded to the American Paul Krugman for his analysis of trade patterns and the settlement of economic activities.
55-year-old Krugman is a Neo-Keynesian who teaches at Princeton University and is known for his regular articles for the New York Times.
Krugman is one of the biggest critics of the Bush administration’s economic and foreign policy.
A few months after the September 11, 2001 attacks, during the days of the Enron collapse, Krugman had claimed in a New York Times editorial that this second event was more crucial to US history than the attacks.
A prediction that received not a few polemics in response and was presented to the economist even years later, but today proves to be completely correct.
“I am surprised and also shocked at how quickly the memory of the scandals in the context of the collapses of Enron or Worldcom has disappeared from the public eye,” Krugman said in late 2002.
According to Lorenzo Bini Smaghi of the European Central Bank’s Executive Committee, Krugman is a “high-value economist” but also a banaliser with a “very aggressive style, especially directed against the excessive liberalism of the Bush administration.”
Open Office, the third version of the "Anti-Microsoft" package will be released
The day of the release of OpenOffice.org 3.0 has come; the open source software is gaining a growing number of users, both at home and in the office, both among freelancers and in the public administration, as a free replacement for Microsoft's Office.
After a year of intensive work by the volunteer developers, which is supervised by SUN Microsystems, the new open office is now presented to the public with some novelties: in addition to a revised and now more Spartan-designed initial menu, a compatibility with Apple's operating system Mac OS x has finally been achieved, as well as support for the new ODF (Open Document Format) 1.2 format, i.e. the new standard ISO.
Eight against was also the compatibility with Microsoft's Office 2007, whose new formats (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx) can be read by OpenOffice.
Also interesting are some new features, such as the one that allows you to reduce the size of PowerPoint presentations, which, for example, makes it easier to send them via email. This includes the possibility to import PDF files into graphics editing modules and at the same time preserve the original appearance of the page.
Thus, it is now possible to generate "hybrid" PDF files, which extend the typical graphics of the Adobe format by the elements of a table and a word processing system.
Collaboration is one of the most improved elements of the applications: tables can now be edited by multiple hands by different users, which avoids conflicts when changes occur; in the case of the word processing system, each editor is assigned a fraction to ensure a better correction process.
Some companies are in the process of publishing various OpenOffice features on the internet (on the cloud), while the definitive result is expected to be published in the coming weeks.
The Italian version is available for download at the following link: http://it.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.html. It follows the English version, which has been on the mirrors since Friday.
Apart from Windows and Mac OS, the program is also available for the Linux operating system.
On request, the installation CD can be sent home or to the office.
While free of charge may be an incentive for the distribution of the program in private households, it is precisely in the field of business where OpenOffice could succeed: after all, various public administration institutions and schools have already switched to OpenOffice.
In fact, there is not even a lack of a training offer, which means optimal help for small and medium-sized companies, and thus even opens up business prospects.
OpenOffice consists of five main components: Writer, the Word corresponding text creation program; Calc, the table program that aims at a displacement of Excel; Impress, for creating presentations as with PowerPoint; Dbase for operating databases in place of the more familiar access; and lastly Draw, a graphical module.
The goal for 2008 is to reach 5 million downloads – a goal that can be easily exceeded with already reached 3 million and 600 thousand.
Kohl also tested positive and thus the fourth doping case
A new doping case is opening up within the framework of the last Tour de France: it is the Austrian athlete Bernhard Kohl of the team Gerolsteiner, who is third-ranked and winner of the jersey of the best climber.
The news was published by the daily L'Equipe on its website.
The 26-year-old Kohl from the Gerolsteiner team is the fourth driver to be tested positive for Cera, the third generation Epo, previously the Italians Riccardo Ricc<0xC3><0xB2> and Leonardo Piepoli as well as the German Stefan Schumacher.
The analyses from the blood samples of Kohl are among those carried out in recent weeks by the Losanna and Chatenay-Malabry laboratories.
