THEME INTRODUCTION: THE NEW YORK TIMES QUESTION: IS ITALY RASISTIAN?
Italy, "the former country of emigrants has recently become one of the preferred countries for immigrants", which are only accepted with reluctance.
This is what the New York Times asks in a lengthy article devoted entirely to the subject of racism in Italy, based on the case of the young Abdul William Guibre from Burkina Faso, who was murdered a month ago in Milan after he stole a package of cookies.
The case bears witness to what the Times calls the “paradox of the North”: the northern regions are those with “the most integration and job opportunities” and yet “the highest level of anti-immigration sentiments and the greatest support for the Lega North.”
As a confirmation of the growing tension between Italians and immigrants, the Times refers to further episodes of intolerance from Milan, Rome, Parma, Ciampino and Castel Volturno.
And not just this.
The new legislation introduced by the Lega against immigration and the faster expulsion of illegal immigrants is also cited as a sign of climate change in Italy.
A movement, which also underline the Pope and the President of the State: "Giorgio Napolitano asked the Pope at a meeting at the Quirinal for a cooperation between the Church and the State to combat racism."
Students victims of the up to 900-euro per room high rental prices
The student housing market has no crisis.
According to the latest investigation by Sunia, the tenant union, a single room can cost a student up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples and 600 in Rome.
"This phenomenon has already taken on very serious traits, with large numbers of students actually losing their right to study because their families are unable to support them at this level," said Laura Mariani, head of Sunia, "in these cities, the high demand on the part of the students leads to a distortion of the market, which has also harmed the other residents.
In addition, most rental offers include a number of violations: free contracts, missing registrations, no rental price limit, illicit sub-rents.
For Sunia, there is a need for exceptional measures, which lead to lower rental prices through a revision of the taxation.
If you take a closer look at the investigation, it turns out that in Milan a sleeping space in the Brianza district is needed around 450 euros; a single room starts at 650 euros (in the Bande Nere district) and ends at 800 euros in the Lambiate, Udine and Fiera districts or even 900 euros in the Vittoria district.
In Florence, a sleeping space costs on average 350/400 euros, a room 700.
In Bologna, where students concentrate in the neighborhoods around the university, 250/280 euros are for a bed of necessity, 370 to 500 for a single room.
In Rome, the prices in the neighborhoods around the university are about 600 euros for a single room, 450 for a sleeping place in a double room.
Only a little lower are the rents in the neighborhoods around the other universities of Rome: 550 euros in Ostiense and Cinecitt<0xC3><0xA0>.
Only those who dodge outside can save money: 300 euros for a sleeping place and 450 euros for a single room in Prenestina, Centocelle and similar quarters.
In Naples you need 300-450 euros for a sleeping place, for a room the price is between 400 and 600 euros in the most expensive neighborhoods, the Policlinico, Vomero and Colli Aminei.
In Bari a sleeping place costs 250-350 euros, a single room at least 350.
In the smallest cities, prices are lower, but they have a greater weight in the urban economy.
In cities where the phenomenon of renting to non-European students is more common, such as in Perugia, there is even another anomaly: renting that is 25-30% above the average is demanded by foreign students.
Farewell to the old Paradiso cinema – the cities close their historic cinema halls
The historic cinemas close due to the favored multiplex cinemas.
“A city without cinemas is a blind city, like a face without eyes.”
This image by director Giuseppe Tornatore is an effective description of what is currently happening in the major urban centers of Italy, and also in the provinces.
The process of exclusion of cinemas, which began with the birth of the large multi-room complexes in the periphery, means in the long run death for the one-room cinema in the center. A process that not only seems inevitable and irrevocable, but also carries the traits of a cultural crime.
“It’s like losing a friend with whom you’ve covered a piece of street full of emotions,” says the director of the film “Nuovo Cinema Paradiso”, which won him the Oscar and the Grand Prix of Cannes 20 years ago. It’s the story of a suburban cinema and its nostalgia for living in a world that is probably lost forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the central trade association, speak a clear language: in the last five years, the enormous number of 316 traditional cinemas have had to close; these miners paid for the majority of the cinemas in the major cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
The regions most affected include Emilia-Romagna with 82 lost cinemas, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
This shows that the main culprits are the multiplex cinemas, because it is precisely these three regions in which the largest number of these modern cinemas have been registered: with 195 in the last 5 years, Lombardy leads the lists, 81 are in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"The business has evolved in an irrational way," says Paolo Protti, President of Anec, "it is useful that new structures are also created, but the first is the preservation of the already existing, because if a hall closes in the city, not all its regular customers are willing to visit a multiplex cinema in the periphery instead of the old one.
And here still remains the missing budget for the fund of the trade association: the debt burden recorded by the state is about 10 million euros.
It is a shame from an ethical and moral point of view that the government fails to observe the existing laws.
To maintain the sector, between 16 and 18 million euros per year would be necessary.
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, due to fears about the old cinemas, decided to protect them through an agreement between the municipality and the Anec; it is the first agreement of its kind in Italy that aims to protect and support the traditional cinemas, both in the historical center and in the periphery.
The measures envisaged include tax provisions for cinema operators as well as benefits for the public with regard to local transport: it will be possible to drive into the traffic-limited areas of the centre and also to park at cheaper parking fees.
"It is a welcome initiative," says Giuseppe Tornatore, "I hope that other cities will join our example and also design new concepts.
Of course, we also need better audio and video equipment to be able to align something against the superpower of multiplex rooms, because after all, today’s audience is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema has always been an important topic for me: the closure of the "Supercinema" of Baghiera, the place of my childhood and youth, was the decisive point that led me to found the "Nuovo cinema Paradiso", even though I had played with the thought for 10 years.
I have been living in Rome for 25 years; when I pass the Rialto or the Quirinale in Via Nazionale, where I have experienced so many different emotions, I turn aside so that I do not have to see the dust-covered posters.
The links between politics and 'Ndrangheta lead to the arrest of the mayor of Gioia Tauro
"The mayor of Gioia Tauro was ready to adapt the decisions of the community to the interests of the Piromalli mafia group.
The accusations by the Calabrian Anti-Mafia Lawyer against Mayor Giorgio Dal Torrione and his deputy Rosario Schiavone of the municipality of Gioia Tauro, who were arrested this morning for involvement in mafia businesses, are serious.
In handcuffs, Gioacchino Piromalli, the older intermediary between the clan and the public administration, and his nephew: the lawyer, who bears the same name as the boss of the clan, had already been sentenced for involvement in criminal associations of the mafia, at the time to a compensation sum of 10 million euros.
"Disregarding any kind of moral and legal norm," the lawyers write, "the two local administrations had decided to pay the lawyer Piromalli funds for advisory activities."
According to the judges, this made it possible for the mafia group to officially enter the town halls and to participate in the policy of the public administration.
The president of the regional committee of Calabria Agazio Loiero does not deny that in his region "it is anything but an exception to encounter connections of local administrations and organized crime." "There are places where the concentration of the mafia is greater than in others where such connections are practically inevitable.
But there are also local politicians who resist the pressure of the 'Ndrangheta: heroes who keep a white vest."
This morning's arrests follow those of last July, with which, according to the police, the Piromalli clan was beheaded.
Since the end of last April, the municipal council of Gioia Tauro had been dissolved, but already in 1991 – and also then due to alleged links between organized crime and the local administration – the local politicians had been removed from their municipal offices.
Giorgio Dal Torrione, then mayor of the Udc, has been elected as the head of the centre-right coalition after the vote in May 2006.
He shouted scandal as the prefecture ordered the dissolution of the municipal council.
He sued Deputy Interior Minister Marco Minniti, whom he accused of inventing everything for political and strategic reasons, but the judges say in connection with this morning’s arrest warrant that the Piromalli clan had even dared to request a change to the A3 project.
From an interrogation action in connection with the investigations into the Dal Torrione case, the willingness to respond to the wishes of an entrepreneur, known to be a representative of the large group around the Piromalli, has been shown – thus making the actions of the public administration identical to the interests of this clan.”
When the energy comes out of the waves, suddenly the big ones run up.
It is a non-fading source of money that covers over 70% of the planet’s surface and only now do the world’s big energy companies seem to understand this.
Waves, currents and tides are the new renewable energy sources that everyone is now looking at, and also looking to occupy, such as giants like Chevron.
The possibility of obtaining energy from the movements of the sea has been considered and studied for 70 years; it is not by chance that these studies have intensified considerably since the first oil crisis.
When the price of oil collapsed around 1980, the idea of marine energy was forgotten, but now environmental organizations and the rising price of oil are pushing for new impetus in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of global energy needs could be met by the energy generated by ocean waves.
This would be equal to twice the amount of energy currently produced by nuclear power plants.
In addition, there are also the currents and tides.
Giants in attack.
The first company to invest in marine energy is Enersis, which signed a contract in 2005 to build a power plant in the north of Portugal.
When this news was published, it seemed to be a revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more companies from the traditional energy sector are now relying on marine energy generation.
“Chevron is investigating these technologies,” said the spokesman of a company known to the American giant in the Wall Street Journal, “and is weighing the possibility of collaborating with us.”
This is about obtaining an authorization from the American Energy Commission, which is necessary to start a project off the coast of Alaska.
This is a sign not to be underestimated, especially considering that the U.S. continues to pump oil in Alaska, and President Bush has only recently launched plans for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, New York-based Verdant Power Inc. and New Jersey-based Ocean Power are also investing in the new industry; if the details are not known, observers are talking about increasing interest.
technologies that can be improved.
Experts speak of a technology that is still in the making, not least since the last doubts from environmentalists have not yet been clarified.
So far, projects such as those in Portugal and Scotland are rather small in size and do not seem to cause any serious environmental problems.
However, in order to produce energy on a large scale, technologies with a much greater impact on the environment are needed.
There are several options: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of interconnected buoys.
The thrust of the shafts, which moves the buoys up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure within the floats by means of pistons and cylinders.
This drives a turbine, which in turn operates a generator.
The electricity is then sent to the coast via underwater pipelines.
So far, there are four planned installations of this kind, which are only waiting for state approval, and some of the energy obtained could also be used for military installations.
However, Verdant Power already produces energy for a department store and a parking lot using subsea turbines in the East River of New York.
The water movements during the tides drive the turbines, which feed the generator as a result of the resulting rotational movement.
According to Verdant, a long queue of potential clients is already waiting for the necessary authorizations to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tides.
According to the Institute for Electricity Generation Research, special interest deserves at the moment the potential that lies in the tides.
Although it is also an irregular phenomenon, the tides are better predictable than wind currents, solar radiation and also the waves, and therefore a more reliable source of electricity.
It is precisely tidal energy that has led states such as New York, Maine and Alaska, as well as other coastal states, to invest $7.5 million in 2008 – up to 35 million are already planned for 2009.
